                  <h5> <a name="gov"></a>Government </h5>
                  <p>The fono (Legislative Assembly) comprises 49 members. 47 represent the indigenous Samoan population and are elected by popular vote for a three year term. Only traditional chiefs (mataii) are eligible to be candidates. The 2 remaining members represent Samoans of foreign extraction, and are elected on a separate roll. 

                  <p>The member who commands a majority in parliament (through 
                    a secret ballot) is appointed Prime Minister. The Prime Minister 
                    selects the 12 members of the cabinet. The constitution provides 
                    for a Head of State selected from one of the four Chiefdoms 
                    (tama aiga). The current Head of State holds the position 
                    for life but, in the future, Heads of State will be elected 
                    by the fono for a five year term. The Head of State does not 
                    play an active role in government, although he appoints the 
                    Prime Minister (on the fono's recommendation) and must approve 
                    the laws passed by the fono. 
                  <p>Local fonos, at the village level, have wide powers of administration.

                  <h5><a name="res"></a>Resources<br>
                  </h5>
                  <p>Agriculture is the main economic activity. Most of the population 
                    subsists on traditional farming and some of the country's 
                    main exports are agricultural crops, such as coconuts (and 
                    derived products such as coconut cream and coconut oil), taro, 
                    breadfruit, bananas and cocoa. A significant part of this 
                    production is sent to the thousands of ex-pat Samoans (living 
                    mainly in New Zealand, Australia, Hawaii and California). 
                    Remittances from Samoans living abroad play a major part in 
                    the country's economy. 
                  <p>Exports to Australia of wire harnesses produced by a Japanese electrical equipment company established in Apia provide most of the country's foreign earnings. Tourism is an expanding sector. The country still depends on foreign assistance for its financial survival and economic development, the main donors being Japan, Australia, New Zealand and the EU.



                  </p>
                  <h5><a name="hist"></a>History </h5>
                  <p>Archaeological research suggests that Samoa was first settled about 1000 BC by people coming from either Fiji or Tonga. 

<p>The first European to visit Samoa was the Dutch navigator Jacob Roggeveen in 1721, followed in 1768 by the Frenchman Antoine de Bougainville. 

                  <p>The islands were visited during the 19th century by a succession 
                    of missionaries, explorers and traders. Amongst them, August 
                    Unshelm from the firm Godeffroy und Sohn, who established 
                    the first German presence in the Pacific in 1856. By 1870, 
                    the company had acquired some 30,000 hectares of land on Upolu 
                    island and established agencies in most islands of the Central 
                    and Western Pacific. 
                  <p>Following years of rivalry between the three foreign powers in the region - Germany, Britain and the United States - Samoa was divided in two parts: the eastern part was controlled by the US Navy, while the western part was annexed by Germany. 

<p>In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Western Samoa was occupied by a New Zealand military force. After the war, under the Treaty of Versailles, Western Samoa was placed under New Zealand mandate. The years of New Zealand administration were marked by the rise of the Mau, a passive resistance movement opposed to the New Zealand presence. 

                  <p>After World War II, Samoa became a Trust Territory of the 
                    United Nations still administered by New Zealand. It became 
                    independent on 1 January 1962. It changed its name from Western 
                    Samoa to Samoa in 1997. 
                  <h5>Main Issues </h5>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>threat to the 'Samoan way' caused by economic development 
                        (tourism) and the return of Samoans from overseas<br>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <p> </p>
                    <li>
                      <p>high level of emigration to New Zealand<br>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
